Prunus caroliniana, also known as Carolina Cherry Laurel, is a species of evergreen tree.
It is native to the Southeastern United States and Mexico.
The tree can grow up to 40 feet tall and has a dense, pyramidal shape.
Its leaves are glossy, dark green, and can grow up to 6 inches long.
The tree produces small white flowers in the spring followed by small black fruits in the fall.
It is commonly used as a landscape tree for its attractive foliage and tolerance to a variety of soil types.
However, its seeds and leaves are toxic if ingested by humans and animals.
